+ Using the above definition of equality, the empty set axiom, and the axiom for building sets pairwise, prove that the following sets are distinct: $\phi, \{\phi\}, \{\{\phi\}\}, \{\phi, \{\phi\}\}$.

Hypothesis:

$$
  \begin{align}
    A = B \rightarrow (\forall x, x \in A \rightarrow x \in B) \wedge (\forall x, x \in B \rightarrow x \in A) \tag 1 \\
    \forall x, x \not\in \phi \tag 2 \\
    \forall x, x \in \{a\} \leftrightarrow x = a \tag 3 \\
    \forall x, x \in \{a, b\} \leftrightarrow (x = a) \wedge (x = b) \tag 4
  \end{align}
$$

Proof:

By the above properties of equality being transitive, to show that a certain collection of sets are distinct, it is sufficient to show pairwise inequality upto transitivity.

$$
  \begin{align*}
    (\phi \in \{\phi\}) \wedge (\phi \not\in \phi) & \rightarrow \phi \neq \{\phi\} & \textrm{by (3), (2), and (1)} \\
    (\{\phi\} \in \{\{\phi\}\}) \wedge (\{\phi\} \not\in \{\phi\}) & \rightarrow \{\phi\} \neq \{\{\phi\}\} & \textrm{by (3) and (1)} \\
    (\phi \in \{\phi, \{\phi\}\}) \wedge (\{\phi\} \in \{\phi, \{\phi\}\}) & \rightarrow \textrm{no two are equal} & \textrm{by (4) and (1)}
  \end{align*}
$$

